{"/service/ndnp/dlc/batch_dlc_carmichael_ver01/data/sn83045462/00280657530/1924052401/0800.xml":{"full_text":"WALLOONS COMPOSE\nHALF OF BELGIUM\nConstitute French-Speaking Sec\ntion of Racially Divided\nNation,\nHAVE LO2JG BEEN LEADERS\nEarly Sought Religious Liberty in\nNew World.\nTo the question \u201cWhat is a Wal\nloon?\u201d that arises from the Issuance\nby the United States of a special\nHuguenot Walloon New Netherlands\ntercentenary postage stamp and coin\nand the holding of New York's New\nNetherlands celebration, one answer\nmight he \"half a Belgian,\" according\nto a bulletin from the Washington\nheadquarters of the National Geo\ngraphic Society.\n\"The name \u2018Walloon,\u2019 says the bul\nletin, \u201cis little known on this side of\nthe Atlantic, even less so than \u2018Flem\ning-, because both have been merged\nin the national name \u2018Belgian.\u2019 It is\na fact, however, that instead of the\nBelgians having racial unity they\nconsist of two peoples approximately\nequally divided, speaking languages\ndiffering almost as widely as Swedish\nand Spanish. But though racially\nand linguistically the Belgians make\nup a sort of a house divided against\nitself, politically and religiously they\nconstitute as staunch a national en\ntity as does French-German-Italian\nspeaklng Switzerland, and uicy have\nstood together through the <*enturies\nunder various rulers.\nWalloons Plus Flemings.\n\"The Walloons may be said to form\nthe French-speaking half of Belgium,\nfor though a very few in out-of-the\nway districts know only the French\nlike old Walloon language, modern\nFrench has replaced that speech for\nthe vast majority of the Walloons.\nThe other half of the Belgian part\nnership is made up by the Flemings,\nwhose speech, Flemish, differs very\nlittle from Dutch. The Catholic peo\nple of Flanders, however, have been\ndivided from their kinsmen, the Prot\nestant Dutch, by a religious gulf for\nhundreds of years and prefer to\n\u2022'leave to. their fellow-religionists, the\nWalloons.\nLine of Demarkalioii,\n\u201cAn almost straight line can be\ntraced on the surface of Belgium\nseparating the Walloons from the\nFlemings. It runs from Aix-la-Cha\npelle, just Inside the German border,\nwestward to strike the French bound\nary a short distance southeast of\nTpres. There \u2019is little to indicate this\nline to the eye of the traveler who\ncrosses it, but his ear will soon tell\nhim that he has passed from one lan\nguage zone, to another. The line\nmarks what was once the edge of a\ndense forest covi ring the rough land\nof southern Belgium.\nWalloons Pushed Hack.\n\"To this line the old Walloons\u2014the\nBalgae of Julius Caesar\u2014were pres-s\n--ed by the southward-faring Teutons,\nwho took possession of and cultivated\nthe plains and swamps of northern\nBelgium. Those immigrant Teutons,\nfrom whom the Flemish people\nsprang, did not penetrate the forest\ncountry, and there the Walloons re\nmained intrenched. Save for iso\nlated groves, ttie forest has disap\npeared today, giving place to mines,\nfactories, farms and gardens, but the\nFlemish-Walloon racial lino is almost\naa sharply marked as it was 1,409\nyears ago.\n\"The Walloons in their native land\ntoday are practically all Catholics,\nbut there were religious differences\namong them in the seventeenth cen\ntury. and it was fugitive Protestant\nWalloons who played a prominent\npart in peopling America. While the\nSpanish were endeavoring to root out\nheresy in the Netherlands hundreds\nof thousands of both Walloons and\nFlemings fl\u00ab-d to the newly set up\nProtestant Dutch republic, just as\nseme of tile Pi!gram fathers fled\nthere from England. It was Wal\nloons from among these fugitives\nwho. like the Pilgrims and French\nHuguenots, emigrated to America.\nNew York Was \u201cNow Vvcsnes.\u201d\n\"In the first ship sent to the pres\nent territory of the United States by\nthe Dutch West India Company, the\nNew Netherland. Which landed in\nthe Hudson River in 1623. Walloons\nled by Jesse de Forest were passen\ngers. The eight families left on Man\nhattan. which was named 'New\nAvesnes,\u2019 constituted the first settle\nment of that now famous and val\nuable island and the first home\nmakers, in fact, in the middle states.\nThe next and succeeding years\nbrought more Dutch than Walloon\nImmigrants and, though the latter\nplayed important parts in the new\nland, they were eventually swallowed\nup in the Dutch and Huguenot com\nmunities. just as New Avesnes was\nswallowed up by New Amsterdam.\n\"Since they came into existence\nfrom a merging of the old Gallic\nBelgae and the Romans the Wal\nlons have given leaders 10 important\nhistorical movements. Charlemagne\nand Charles Martel may be consid\nered among the original Walloons.\nPeter the Hermit, preacher of the\nfirst crusade, who started one of\nthe most important movements his\ntorically and socially that the world\nhas ever known, was a Walloon; so\nwas Godfrey of Bouillon, who led\nthis initial expedition of Europe's\nchivalry to the Holy Land.\nBed Belgian Revolution.\n\u201cAs a people the Walloons have also\nbeen leaders. The revolution of 1830.\nwhich separated the Belgians from\nTheir temporary connection with Hol\nland, was led largely by the Wal\nloons. The new Belgium, then set up,\nwas begun as a French-speaking\ncountry. Recognition of the claims\nof the Flemings since, however, has\nbrought about the passage of laws\nplacing the two languages on an\nequal footing.\n\"Liege, one of the earliest Belgian\ntowns to suffer from the German in\nvasion during the world war, is the\ncenter of Wallonia, or \u2018the Walloon\ncountry,\u2019 as the French-speaking por\ntion of Belgium is termed. Much of\nthe region is dotted with fine old\nchateaus and the newer country places\nof wealthy city dwellers. Roughly,\nWallonia is Belgium\u2019s factory, while\nFlanders is its garden.\u201d\nIP ALL ROADS IEADTO ODR STORE\nI NO BARKING BISTRICTIOHS-HO-MIAYS-SCTMCE\nI LOUIS HARUG HARDWARES\nS*. CORNER K STS. MW\nIn^ii 11\nHi i pa*iS>>\u00bbWc\u00bb I\nL BRARV I\nBabeaoid Shingle, Roofing, TO\u00bb\u00bb\u00ab FgpA\u00bb Heaters. I\nH Monad Paints, Cbantpell Builders\u2019 Hardware ffl\nI Electric, Gas and OH Ranges [U\nWhen Yen Think of Hardware\nThink of Hartig I\nREAL ES TA TE\nALEXANDRIA.\nALEXANDRIA, Va., May 24 (Spe\ncial). \u2014A series of accidents last\nnight caused damage estimated at more\nthan SI,OOO.\nMiss B. A. Rose, colored, 509 South\nColumbus street, had her car dam\naged badly, and a machine operated\nby Norman Fitzgerald was crushed\nbetween the street car and a car\nparked at the curb.\nFollowing this the truck from No.\nI fire engine house in attempting to\ntake the curve at King and Royal\nstreets and trying at the same time\nto avoid the other accidents crashed\ninto a machine belonging to E. A.\nNines, 404 King street, throwing it to\nthe sidewalk. Daniel Pfiel, 214 North\nRoyal street, and Elmo Muddiman,\nNorth Rosemont, were knocked from\ntheir feet and suffered severe bruises.\nThe truck, which was driven by Os\ncar Cook, also was badly damaged.\nRose, when heard in Police Court\nthis morning, was blamed for the ac\ncident by Judge Duvall, who held\nthat she had no right to stop in a\nrestricted parking area. She was dis\nmissed, however, because she testi\nfied that she had merely stopped to\ndischarge a passenger when Fitzger\nald tried to pass her and was struck\nby the swing of a Washington-Vir\nginia railway car as it attempted to\nmake the turn.\nMissing Veteran Located.\nW. Clinton Riley, world war vet\neran, who disappeared from his home\nhero March 4, leaving destitute his\nwife and three small children, has\nbeen located and is living in East\nChicago, Ind., according to advices\nreceived by Director of Public Safety\nPaul Morton this morning\nThe discovery of the veteran was\nmade through the veterans\u2019 sub\nstation In South Bend, Ind., which\nInvestigated in accordance with a\nposter prepared and circulated by the\npolice department here.\nHis wife, who severaJ weeks after\nhis disappearance, left for her for\nmer home In Coventry, R. 1., will he\nnotified immediately of her husband\u2019s\nwhereabouts. The information was\ncontained in a letter from Byron. R.\nPatton, chief of the information and\nco-operative department of the Vet\nerans\u2019 Bureau.\nFred W. Cr ox ton. who was wanted\nhere for passing a forged certified\ncheck of Walter Drewry and on four\nother persons, yesterday was sen\ntenced to serve three years in the\nMaryland state penitentiary by the\ncourts of Frederick, Md.\nMemorial Exercises,\nOnly a few of the grizzled veterans\nof the war between the states will\nmarch in the thin gray line which\nthis afternoon will pay homage and\ntribute at the graves of their comrades\nof '6l.\nTheodore Harris will deliver the\nConfederate Memorial day eulogy. A\nchoir will sing and a detachment\nfrom Fort Humphreys will fire a\nsalute as the few remaining veterans\ndecorate the resting place of thirty\nfour of their unknown dead who rest\ntogether in a single tomb In Christ\nChurch yard.\nCharles Hedges. Agnewville, Prince\nWilliam County, was arrested yester\nday after state officers captured on\nhis place a 1.000-gallon copper still.\nThis is one of the largest stills ever\ntaken in the state, according to Virgil\nWilliams, who led the raiding party.\n\nROCKVILLE.\nROCKVILLE. Md-, May 24 (Spe\ncial) \u2014In honor of the senior class\nof the Rockville High School, and\nwith about ninety guests in attend\nance, including the members of the\nclass, former students of the school,\nmembers of the schoo\u2019l faculty and\nformer and present county school of\nficials, a banquet was given at the\nMontgomery Country Club here last\nevening. Rev. Nolan B. Harmon, jr.,\npastor of the Methodist Church, was\ntoastmaster and toasts were respond\ned to by Prof. Harry S. Beall, prin\ncipal of the school; Robert E. L.\nSmith, president of the board of\nschool trustees; George H. Lamar,\nformer member of the board of edu\ncation; Prof. Edwin W. Broome, coun\nty superintendent of schools, and Al\ndis Robertson, president of the senior\nclass. Miss Jessie Vandiver of Wash\nington entertained with songs and\nrecitations. The affair was in charge\n\u2022if a committee, of which Miss Hazel\nLong was chairman.\nRev. William B. Waters of Rock\nville, well known evangelist, will be\ngin a series of special services in the\nMethodist Church at Germantown\nSunday morning, June 1. The serv\nices will continue several weeks.\nMemorial Exercise*.\nSenator Lynn J. Frazier of North\nDakota will be the principal speaker\nat memorial exercises to be held in\nthe Methodist Church at Hunting Hill,\nthis county, the evening of May 30.\nThe occasion also will mark the\nformal opening of the church's new\ncommunity hall.\nA large number of guests from this\ncounty, Washington and elsewhere\nattended a dance in St. Mary\u2019s Hall\nhere last evening, which was given\nby the choir of St. Mary\u2019s Catholic\nChurch. It was In charge of a com\nmittee consisting of Miss Lucille\nFisher, J. Harry Gormley and Pres\ncott Fisher. The chaperons were Mrs.\nF. Hazel Ca shell, Mrs. W. Harry\nBeard, Mrs. F. Bache Abort and Miss\nRose Dawson. The music was fur\nnished by a Washington orchestra\nand during the evening refreshments\nwere served. The hall was attractive\nly decorated.\nFor violations of motor vehicle reg\nulations, collaterals were forfeited In\nthe police court hero as follows:\nJohn A. R-ussell, S2O; E. N. Fairchild\nand O. R. Lewis, $7.50 each.\nA license has been Issued for the\nmarriage of Hulley W. Calson,\ntwenty-one years old, and Miss Nellie\nR. Moore, aged nineteen, both of\nHopewell, Va.\nThe Montgomery County League\nbase ball season opens this after\nnoon, Rockville playing at Bethesda,\nWashington Grove at Boyds and\nDickerson at Glen Echo.\nGEM THIEF\u2019S RUSE WORKS.\nTOULOUSE, Franca, May 24.\n\"Somebody smashed a basket of eggs\nin front of your store,\u201d said a well\ndressed stranger to the proprietor of\na Jewelry shop In the Place President\nWilson yesterday. The Jeweler took\na broom and went out to clean up the\nmess. When he returned the stranger\nhad vanished and so had a case con\ntaining 100,000 francs\u2019 worth of Jewels.\nTHE EVENING STAR, WASHINGTON, D. C., SATURDAY. MAY 24, 1924.\nREICHSBANK POLICY\nDRAWS BROADSIDE\nIndustrial Interests Charge Busi\nness Thrown Into General\nLiquidation.\nCREDITS SUDDENLY HALT\nMushroom Financiers Blamed for\nMuch of Distress.\nBy Radio to The Star and the Chicago Daily\nNews. Copyright. 1924.\nBY EDGAR ANSEL MOWRER.\nBERLIN, May 24.\u2014The industrially\nsubsidized newspapers and friends of\nindustry are beginning a broadside on\nDr. Schacht for the Reichsbank credit\npolicy which, It is claimed, has thrown\nbusiness suddenly into general liqui\ndation.\nThe Reichsbank gave credits during\nthe first quarter of 1924 at 10 per cent,\nconsiderably lower than outside\nprices. Then on April 7 It suddenly\nstopped almost completely. Business\nmen who had been resorting to\nReichsbank loans for expanding busi\nness, unmindful of the threatening\nstorm, were suddenly cast adrift.\nMnahroom Banka In Way.\nIt is symptomatic that despite the\nbusiness depression and bankruptcies\nthe number of financial institutions\nand banks in Germany is still 25 per\ncent higher than in 1913, whereas\nbusiness is not much over half. Critics\nbelieve that until those mushroom\nfinanciers are swept away there will\nbe no relief for business.\nThe Reichsbank credit policy was\nguided by a desire to help the farm\ners who. after shame-faced profiteer\ning during inflation, suddenly found\nprices of financial products lower\nthan in 1913, whereas manufacturers'\nprices were about double. It must be\nsaid that businessmen also profiteered\nshamefully, and even now are strug\ngling desperately from borrowing\ncartels and keep prices high rather\nthan liquidate and begin on a sound\nbasis.\nMany havif been borrowing money\nat 2 per cent monthly from banks and\nrelending it at 6 per cent. Others\nhave refused to pay bills even when\nable, throwing the banks, and have\nresisted successfully attempts to\nforeclose.\nSo-called government supervision\ncreated during the war por presum\nably solvent but capitalless firms to\nobtain a kind of private moratorium\nfor a year, has been shamefully\nabused. But now the pinch has come.\nFour hundred and eighty-three notes\nwere protested in Berlin in a single\nthe first of the year fifty\nbanking firms have failed. The num\nber of bankrupt firms is large. The\nofficial number of bankruptcies,\nwhich was only 113 fop the first quar\nter of 1924, rose to 139 in the single\nmonth of April. Statistics for May\nare still unavailable, but are Increas\ning by geometric progression.\nIt Is considered that the business\ndepression In Germany is only begin\nning.\nBULGARIA WINS FAVOR.\nMay Be Able to Enter Little En\ntente, Benes Says.\nBy Radio to The Star and Chicago Daily\nNews. Copyright, 1924.\nSOFIA, May 2 4.\u2014Much interest has\nbeen aroused here by the declaration\nof Edouard Benes, premier of Czecho\nslovakia, that In the future Bulgaria\nmight be able to enter the little en\ntente.\nUntil now the entente has always\nregarded Bulgaria mistrustfully, but\nlately Rumania\u2019s attitude has become\nmore friendly, while a big tobacco\ndeal has had the effect of bettering\nrelations between Bulgaria and\nCzechoslovakia.\nWhat would be the attitude of\nJugoslavia, the third member ot the\nentente, toward Bulgaria's entry re\nmains problematical, but. in any case,\nopinion here welcomes M. Benes\u2019 dec\nlaration as further r r \u00b0of that Bul\ngaria's stock is going up abroad.\nWould Unite Russian Sects.\nBy the Associated Press.\nMOSCOW. May 24.\u2014Rosta. the Bol\nshevik news agency, announces that\nPatriarch Tikhon has declared for co\noperation of the orthodox church\nwith the \u201cliving church\u201d and has ad\ndressed a message to the clergy pro\nposing the formation of diocesan\ncouncils to prepare for an all-Russian\nassembly to be attended by the\npriests of both sections.\nTwo Ways of Looking at It.\nFrom the Boston Transcript.\nProfessor\u2014As a success you have\nbeen a failure.\nStude \u2014Yes, but aa a failure I've\nbeen a success.\nI AN ABSOLUTE BARGAIN I\nCOLUMBIA HEIGHTS\nI 4510 13th Street N.W.\nH Eight Rooms 25 Feet Wide\nGarage\nb| Thoroughly Modem\nIHI SI,OOO Cash Balance Monthly\nPll Newly Decorated\nII Open and Lighted \u2022Saturday and\nH Sunday\u20149 A.M, to 9 P.M,\n\u00a5%iQ/mX SHAPIRO CO\nqiq ivu\nTraruclm iho\nBradley Hills\nWashington\u2019s Country Club District\nVilla sites and acreage properties facing or adjacent\nto the Congressional Country Club, the Burning Tree\nGolf Club and the Montgomery Country Club, which has\nbeen purchased by the Bradley Hills Syndicate, Inc.\nBradley Road is the main thoroughfare through the\nacres of the Bradley Hills Properties which begin at\nthe northwest corner of the Chevy Chase Golf Club and\nextend beyond the Congressional Country Club.\nDesirable Home Sites in \u201cThe English Village,\u2019 Hill\nmead,\u201d \u201cMontgomery Club\u201c Burning Tree\u201d and \u201cCon\ngressional\u201d subdivisions.' Prices on request. If you de\nsire an SBOO lot, or a villa site, or an estate, yon make no\nmistake when you\nBUY IN BRADLEY HILLS\nInquiries in person, telephone or letter receive in\ntelligent answer, without annoyance.\nMiddaugh Shannon, Inc.\nSince 1899\u2014N0 Place Like Home; No Home Like Ours\nRigga-Semme* Bldg., Dupont Circle, Potomac 2200\nUtmbtr Washington Real Estate Board.\nPRAYER BOOK CHANGE\n0. K.\u2019D BY EPISCOPALIANS\nGeneral Council of Church Is Told\nEvery Missionary Pronounced\nFundamentalist.\nBy the Aasoclatod Press.\nPHILADELPHIA, May 24. Two\nchanges In the prayer book used by\nthe Reformed Episcopal Church in the\nUnited States and Canada were adopt\ned yesterday by the general council of\nthe church at a meeting here. Bishop\nelect Robert W. Peach of Newark. N.\nJ., said the alternate form of evening\nprayer contained in the present book\nhad been abolished and a slight\nchange made in the prayer for for\ngiveness which follows general con\nfession.\nIn a statement'for the board of for\neign missions, H. H. Sinnamon de\nclared that every member of the body\nwas a pronounced fundamentalist and\nwould brook the expression of no mod\nernist theories by its missionaries in\nthe field.\nTwo appropriations of $5,000 each\nwere voted for church expansion in\nthe south and Vancouver. B. C. Two\nthousand dollars was donated the Re\nformed Episcopal Church in England\nfor publicity work.\nThe committee on the constitution\nand canons adopted the proposal of\nfered by the general committee, which\nenlarges and makes the duties of the\nlatter committee more powerful.\ninventTopT of war tanks\nCLAIMED BY AMERICAN\nAnker Holth Will Go to London,\nWhere His Evidence Will\nBe Presented.\nBy fable to The Star and Chicago Dally\nNews. Copyright. 1924.\nCHRISTIANIA, May 24.\u2014\u201c0n Amer\nica\u2019s behalf, I claim the honor of hav\ning invented the tanks made famous\nin the great war.\u201d That statement\nwas made today by Anker Holth, a\nNorwegian, who now has become an\nAmerican citizen, living in Los An\ngeles.\nHolth has quietly been preparing\nhis evidence and now announces his\nintention of going to London, where\na commission will decide who should\nhe regarded as the inventor of the\ntank.\nHolth worked as a chief engineer\nfor the International Harvester Com\npany until ISS6, and later conducted\nhis own engineering agency in Chi\ncago. In 1900 he constructed a ma\nchine here which drew ten sixteen\nton plows. This he placed on a cater\npillar system of traction. The ma\nchine was steered by applying differ\nent speeds to the caterpillar belts on\neach side, which is exactly the sys\ntem used in steering tanks.\nRoyalty to Greet Movie Stars.\nMADRID. May 24.\u2014Mary Pickford\nand Douglas Fairbanks will be pre\nsented to King Alfonso and Queen\nVictoria today on their return to Mad\nrid from a visit to Andalusia, Toledo\nand other places of historical In\nterest in Spain. A series of enter\ntainments has been arranged In honor\nof the American movie couple, among\nthem a dinner at the American em\nbassy. tojtake place before their pres\nentation to the king and queen.\nWhat does not happen In a thousand\nyears may happen in a moment.\nj CLEVELAND PARK~\nUnusually Attractive\nCorner Home\nContaining 9 rooms, 3 baths, senr\nani\u2019s room In basement, built-in\ngarage: hardwood floors throughout;\nlargo attic, sun room. Inclosed sleeping\nporch: plenty of shade; exceptionally\nlow priced; very attractive terms.\nOpen for Inspection\nSat., 6\u20149 P.M.\nSun., I\u20146 P.M-\nE. W. BOWLES\n1653 Pa. Ave.\nMala 10.1 K\nOpposite War and Navy Bldg. 25*\nPRESS CHANGES TONE\nAS WOODS DEPARTS\nJapanese Turn From Recrimina\ntions at Exclusion to Eulo\ngizing; Envoy.\nTRACE ACTION TO CONGRESS\nFear End of Relations if Hamhara\nResigns.\nBY E. R. EGGGK.\nBy fable to The Star and Chicago Daily\nNews. Copyright, 1924.\nTOKIO, Japan, May 24. \u2014The ver\nnacular newspapers continue to sound\nthe praises of Ambassador Cyrus E.\nWoods and to express deep regret\nat hl\u00bb resignation. While the de\nparture of the envoy Is undoubtedly\na great loss to American interests\nhere, coming as It does at the time of\na serious crisis, It has had the effect\nof stemming the rising tide of bitter\nness resulting from the exclusion\nclause In the American immigration\nbill. Hostile utterances have been re\nplaced by deserved eulogies. Though\nthe friendly expressions show merely\nthe personal regard whieh the Jap\nanese have for Mr. Woods, the psy\nchological effect of the situation is\ncertain to mitigate the anti-American\nfeeling.\nThe selection of a worthy successor\nto Mr. Woods Is regarded by Ameri\ncans her>e as extremely important,\nas President Coolldge\u2019s success in\nfinding a suitable ambassador for the\nTokio post may be a strong factor\nin determining the future relations\nof the United States and Japan. Tin\nbelief still entertained that Mr. Woods\nresigned because of the action of\nCongress on the exclusion clause in\ncreases the regard which the Japa\nnese have for the departing envoy.\n\u201cMan of Lofty Character.\u201d\n\u201cAmbassador Woods,\u201d says the\nTokio Nlohl Niohi Shimbun, \u201cis a\nman of lofty character and a typical 1\nEl I I====inf===nni====inn==irn\nINCOMPARABLE HOMES f\nJ CHEVY CHASE, D. C. 16th ST. HIGHLANDS\nDetached Brick Semi-Detached Brick E\n3713 HARRISON STREET 23\nThe High Character of Neighbors The Splendid Car Service' COLORADO AVLNLJL\n0 e Architectural Beauty The Rigid Zoning Restriction This Residential Masterpiece Is a Bright Example of JT\nThe High Elevation Intelligent Home Planning\nThe Superb Location The Reasonable Price Exceptionally large rooms, where sunshine and fresh air an\nw -T-. \u2022_ Li u C' u- be your constant companions. Living- room with fireplace, 18x22.\n\u2014Makes This the Most Desirable Home in Chevy Chase Dining room 18x20. Breakfast porch, glass Inclosed, llxir.. Bed-\nCenter hall, living room with French doors to porch, splendid chambers and other rooms in proportion. \"Wide and deep lots with\ndining room, large kitchen, pantry. Four chambers, two baths. many shade trees.\ntwo inclosed sleeping porches, maid's room and bath, storage room, This is a home of the most artistic loveliness. It has even\nlarge closets, built-in plumbing fixtures. modern comfort and is surrounded by homes of the highest grade. L\u00bb\npi See this beautiful home at once. It is a wholesome light to Judge the merits of this magnificent residence by inspecting f?\n\u25a0JJ critical eyes. it yourself. U.\nBuilt by F. M. Johnson\u2014All Johnson Homes Are Known for Their Fine Quality of Construction and Finish\nOpen For Inspection Sunday From 10 A.M. to 9 P.M.\nExclusive I 111.1 Heal p\nAgents FTOil\" sf\u00df Q J Estate P\n(LiL l ST.\n1 Among tke Six Remaining i\nof these ten newly offered yr- 4 I\ni CHEVY CHASE HOMES\nare some of the most desirable houses and \u00abE\nchoicest locations in this popular group m\"-\nJust Off and Facing Toward A Beautiful Drive or i\nP| Connecticut Avenue Short Car Ride\nand the Cherry Chase Easily Reached and I I T'\nX Car Line W orth Seeing\nYou Will Be Pleased With The\u2014 |-aPtBE\njj& Charming English doorway and center-hall entrance A\nA Cheery raised brick fireplace in the large front living room|\nX which opens to\nSty Wide English front porch, through full-length French double*\n1 windows. G\ny Roomy dining salon, with artistic wall lights and inclosed break- A\nw fast porch just beyond.\nA Modern kitchen, fully equipped with Detroit Jewel range and if?\nbuilt-in conveniences.\nOutside pantry, with built-in refrigera\nte PVUTTDTT tor separate rear porch and wide yard. e\\*i\\ A\nm LlAlTlDl 1 nUUDE* Four large bedchambers upstairs; nu- JSI M;)(J f\nm merous windows and closets; linen closet 'r v T\n_____ _ 3415 Fessenden St. shower and built-in fixtures in the two Convenient Terms _ n\nwhite-tiled, conveniently located baths. KSSV\nM Floored attic, lighted and high cellinged.\nDry basement: hot and cold water mixing valves in washtubs;\nPittsburg Instantaneous water heater. A\nIdeal hot-water heating plant. v\nt Large lot, 125 feet by 33 feet.\nTBBW Pafved alley; wide street; cement sidewalks.\n,Wm. S. Phillips\nRealtor-Builder 15th and K Sts.\ngentleman In behavior and epeech.\nHe will be greatly missed among the\nJapanese. The rash action of Con\ngress compelled him to resign, but\nwe trust he will continue his efforts\nto promote the mutual friendship of\nthe United States and Japan.\u201d\n\u201cThere are ways of retaliating\nagainst the anti-Japanese measures\nenacted by the American Congress,\nbut we must tender our warm and\nsincere thanks to the ambassador\nwho was made the victim of such\nmeasures,\u201d says the Kokurain Shim\nbun.\nThe Chuo Shlmbun sees great sig\nnificance in the resignation of Am\nbassador Woods. \u201cShould Ambassa\ndor Hnnlharia feel compelled to re\nsign as the result of the anti-Jap\nanese immigration law,\u201d it says, \"the\nJapanese-Arnerican diplomatic rela\ntions must be understood to be sev\nered. This indeed would be deplor\nable.\u201d\n\u201cWe sympathize deeply with Am\nbassador Woods,\u201d says the Chugal\nShogyo Shlmpo, the leading commer\ncial newspaper in Tokio. \u201cWe greatly\nregret his resignation because it\nshows that the anti-Japanese agita\ntion has gone to the extreme and that\nthe exclusion clause has become bind\ning.\"\nThe belief that Ambassador Hani\nhara will resign should the exclusion\nclause become effective persists, de\nspite official denial that the action of\nCongress is regarded as making the\nposition of the envoy untenable. How\never, certain sections of the press\nstrongly urge the necessity of Hani\nhara, remaining in Washington to see\nJapan through in its present difficul\nties.\nSeek to Honor Marx.\nLONDON, May 24 \u2014-The Soviet dele\ngation in London has petitioned the\nBritish government for permission to\nremove the body of Karl Marx from\nHlghgate cemetery, where he was\nburied in 1883, to Moscow for inter\nment in Red Square, according to the\nDaily Express. The newspaper ex\npresses belief that such permission\ncan only be given by members of the\nMarx family.\nObregon Acts in Oil Strike.\nMEXICO CITY, May 24 \u2014President\nObregon has decided to take personal\naction with a view to settlement of\nthe Mexican Eagle Oil Company\nstrike, which has continued for two\nmonths. The president has asked\nboth parties to submit the facts to\nhim.\nREAL EST ATE.\nMAY DELAY CONFERENCE.\nROME, May 24.\u2014From the nego\ntiations going on, the Indication is\nthat the convocation of an inter\nallied conference on reparations may\nbe postponed until after the forma\ntion of a new French cabinet. The\nBelgian government is credited with\nthe intention of suggesting that the\nconference, when held, shall be\ndomiciled in northern Italy, near the\nSwiss frontier, an area which would\nbo convenient for the delegates of\nthe various countries to be repre\nsented.\nIn political circles here the belief\nprevails that a conference on repara\ntions should limit itself to deciding\nthe questions at issue on reparations,\ntaking for granted the good faith of\nGermany\u2019s intentions to fulfill pledges\nbased on the Dawes report, and that\nthere should be no discussion with\nregard to sanctions upon which the\nallied countries may hold conflicting\nviews.\n|HHIIIIIIIIilllllllllllltlllllillllllltllllllillllillll|||UHIillllllllllllllllllllilllllilllllll!||lill||t(inillillllllliil'ltllllllllilliltl||^\nIndividually Designed and Built\nss 3\nCleveland Park Community Group of 3 brick. I\nI Nos. 3543, 3545 and 3547 Quebec Street, $15,500; 1\nsemi-detached, $12,500. Center, semi-detached, has 1\n8 rooms and 2 tiled baths, built-in tub and shower,\nhot-water heat, open fireplace, hardwood floors\nthroughout, cement porches, built-in garage. Cen-\nter house has 6 rooms. Built by day labor.\nH HOW TO REACH PROPERTY\u2014Conn. ave. ars to\nPorter, west on I'orter to 35th st.. north one block t\u00ab. S\nS Quebec, west one block to property; or Wisconsin av\u00bb.\njs to Porter, one block east to Idaho ave., one block\nnorth to Quebec.\nI TERRELL UTILE, Inc. I\n1206 18th St N.W. Main 3285\nEvening Phone Franklin 168<\u00bb-J or West 3118-J s\n\u2018iiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiHiiiiiiiiiHiiiiuiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiiniiiiiHiiiimiiimiininii\nBOOTLEGGING IN HOLLAND\nBy Radio (o The Star and Chicago Pally\nNewa. Copyright, IS;M.\nAMSTERDAM. May 24.\u2014Greatly de\ncreased liquor tax returns for the\nfirst four months of the current year\nare interpreted here as indicating\nnot so much a decrease in drinking\nas a startling increase in liquor\nsmuggling.\nIt is declared that smuggling from\nGerman free ports to Dutch ports\nalong the Zuyder Zee and along the\nGerrnan-Belgian frontier has taken\non unbelievable proportions. Also\nmany clandestine distilleries seem to\nbe springing up in Holland.\nThe newspapers, in denouncing\nthese conditions, raise the question\nwhether Holland is not suffering\nfrom the same evils as the United\nStates. Opinions are expressed that\nofficial figures do not cover more\nthan GO per cent of real liquor con\nsumption here. The only remedy, it\nis said, is lowering liquor taxes,\nwhich would make moonshinlng un\nprofitable.\n21","height":"25077","width":"19716"}}
